text: I'm optimistic about this film but I'm not going to hold my breath.  It already looks "typical" of today's movies especially with the predictable same old formula movie trailer.  I already don't like the premise of Pete being a feral child in the woods.  Pete was never a feral child but an abused runaway.  Now perhaps he stayed in the woods 6 years only to be found again and sent back to some abusive foster home and have Eliot follow him and protect him along the way.  Then it might work.  Just going to have to wait and see i guess.  Having loved the original movie as a child I'm certainly going to go see it and give it a chance but my expectations are not very high for fear of being burned by hollywood again.  Also while not a musical this time around I hope the movie's music is at least half way decent.  It's been a long time now since I've heard a movie soundtrack that is truly moving in an unforgettable way.  Seems like most of the music in movies today is composed of nothing but random orchestral and subwoofer sounds.  I truly miss the days of John Williams, Alan Silvestri, Jerry Goldsmith, Bill Conti, etc.  And Heck I actually loved most of the music in the original Pete's Dragon.  Some of it was a little annoying and prolonged but the songs "Brazzle Dazzle day".  "Swear I Saw a Dragon"  "I love you too", "It's not easy", and of course "Candle on the Water" were all excellent songs with very emotionally uplifting melodies.

text: To everyone complaining about remakes, why? The original still exists, its still great, if you miss that film just re-watch it again. The point of a remake is to let someone with a new vision on the source material tell their version of it, which is exactly what's happening here. I mean in the description it literally says 'reimagining', as in giving a new perspective on the story and not just re-telling it piece by piece. Try judging it as its own film separate from the original and you might have a better time. If you still find you dislike how the movie looks, that's totally fine that's just personal taste and you're not obligated to like it, but hating it because its' not the original' is completely missing the point.

text: As a HUGE fan of the original I'm doing my best to be open-minded for this remake. I'm looking forward to clear shots of Elliot! The promo poster makes him look just a shade terrifying, but then the live Jungle Book animals were downright intimidating in the first trailer, less so once the second one featured more dialog. I don't know who will be taking Charlie Callus's VA role though, that'll be a tough sell for me!  As "Mogwli: Pacific NW" this film appears I think altering his backstory to be a feral child is a LOT more appropriate for 2016. In 1977 he was a child slave ("We Gotta Bill of Sale Right Here") for abusive con artists. It's old jokes and stereotypes that flew in the 70's but aren't OK now (really weren't then either, but you can't ignore the past and just have to rematch with that in mind). As for Howard taking on Helen Reedy's role I just hope the new character avoids the more sexist maternal tropes while still letting her be a possible parent to Pete.

text: What is this bullshit. They take one of my favorite childhood movies and rip it to shreds and put together something that is barely relatable to the main concept.  This isn't some fantasy 'Narnia' bs. Stop trying to make it be.  It's a lighthearted film about a boy without a family, running away from abusive foster family/hillbillies, who is taken under the wing of the lighthouse keeper's daughter as she tries to assimilate him to normal town life while he hides the very big secret of an invisible dragon. It's a funny, heartwarming and genuine story.  Or at least it's supposed to be. Not everything has to be dark and magical. Let Eliot be the big dopey clumsy dragon.    I was excited to see this redone IF it was actually redone the right way. This is just Tarzan/Jungle Book sans animals, add dragon.

text: I had high hopes for this... before I saw the snippet of a preview at the D23 convention this past August.  It was pretty clear then that it wouldn't be a musical and that many significant thematic changes had been made.  I think I'll feel about this the way my Mom feels about Disney's animated adaptation of The Jungle Book: she grew up with her Dad reading her Rudyard Kipling stories, so the wildly divergent Disney telling was kind of an affront to her.  I just went out to iTunes and bought the HD version of the original 1977 Pete's Dragon.  I'll probably just give this new version a miss.

text: For all the nay-sayers: this remake is being done by acclaimed director David Lowry. David Lowery doesn't sugar-coated musical fairy tales. The narrative of his movies feels almost like a folk tale, almost lyrical and dream-like. This is gonna be closer to something like E.T.  then the Pete's Dragon you remember, and to me that's exciting! That's how the story was always meant to be told, and they didn't do that the first time they adapted it. Not that I don't like that version; the original is great. But I'm glad this new version will be nothing like it.

text: I wonder if people would be a lot more optimistic about this movie if it wasn't named "Pete's Dragon"...   I think that people would do themselves and everyone a favor if they DON'T compare this movie to the original. What's the point? They have close to NOTHING in common. Does that automatically make this a horrible movie? Heck no! If you remove the cute, fluffy, musical aspects, you get a plot that's pretty darn intriguing and WELL WORTH a different approach and adaption. Should it never be revisited just because the 70s movie made it first and people don't want to like anything else...?  I loved the original Pete's Dragon. It's one of the dearest movies I still own on VHS. And I think this remake looks promising. But if you feel like your childhood memories are threatened by the mere existence of this, then just pretend it's an entirely different movie. Which it basically is.

text: These comments... "It's absolutely nothing like the original. They are ruining the story" "Thanks for ruining a Classic Disney"  Thanks. We all appreciate your useless input on something you barely know. Unless you have a time machine and went to the future and saw the movie, your assumptions of it, are just that: assumptions.  And no, sweetie, it's not going to ruin a thing about what you saw before. The old story will still be there for you to see and enjoy. You think the new stuff is shit, okay, then don't pay to see it. Do you think someone will be forcing you to see the movie? Just what kind of people do you have around, honestly?  The thing is, you don't see the movie, then keep quiet about it, because deciding something is good or bad based on barely 1:20min of a one/two-hour-something movie it's just pure ignorance. You have no foundation to say if it's really good or not. Like I said, assumptions are not really a valid rate.  You don't like people remaking or changing old stories, then don't see it. Keep seeing the old movies you like and let other people enjoy something we might not have seen before. Not everyone likes the old movies, in case you have a hard time understanding that. And some of us can appreciate the old and the new. All you do saying stuff like that is painting yourself as a ignorant-childish drama queen. It's not really a good thing to be proud about.   Anyway, I'm curious to see how this will turn out.  Have a nice day  :)

text: Hmm...little boy running around in the wild, raised by some kind of realistic-looking CGI animal...leaping over a cliff...yeah, I feel like this & the live-action Jungle Book were conceived together. xD I won't say that it's a horrid disgrace to the original, because it looks as though it takes only the very basic concept (a boy who's friends with a dragon named Elliot), and doesn't simply try to "remake" what we already have. Of course the dragon looks straight outta GoT, but they're obviously going for realism to contrast with the first hyper-cartoony Elliot (and remember The Reluctant Dragon? Yeah, this would seem more "different" from today's standard fare if they went that way again, but...clearly not!) Disappointing that I can't expect it to be musical, but eh, it'll probably be one of the "cute for one viewing" kind of movies, at least.

text: Pete's Dragon... The original classic¬†was the first feature film my parents took me to when I was a boy... One of my favorite childhood¬†movies of all time. This reboot version looks far different from the original version, of course the original was a musical/comedy for kids, this version appears to be a polar opposite of the wholesome family fun the original offered. Whether this modern CGI take still has a similar appeal remains to be seen as the original was nominated for an academy award, thus it has big shoes to fill.

text: Okay, kids, ladies, gentlemen, lentlemen, whatever you identify by. I've learned something when it comes to remakes by watching Rob Zombie's Halloween. I'm sure you've seen it too, and like you, once upon a time, I compared the two movies side by side and the first ten minutes of the movie, I was lamenting on how different this movie was from John Carpenter's version. When I finally set aside my prejudices and was able to let go of the version that John Carpenter made, I enjoyed the movie. Michael Myers is my favorite horror villain and in the JC version there was hardly an explanation for why he snapped and Rob Zombie revealed that mystery for us.  I learned that neither of the movies take away from either version. So! If you love the classic Pete's Dragon, watch it. Watch it, watch it, watch it. Enjoy it for what it is. A movie that was just getting into the baby steps of CGI and the amount of work that went into making it convincing that a dragon was following Pete around town causing all kinds of havoc.   This new movie has my attention. Its intriguing to me because it's set in present day, same as the original movie was. Remakes may make people lament concerning their childhood vision being ripped to pieces, but keep in mind that those who are seem to be 20 and 30 somethings who don't realize that these movies are supposed to be for your kids. Show the originals to your kids, let them watch both movies, but don't for one second, be a shitty adult in the life of any child who may have the misfortune of having to be around you for five minutes and crush a movie you haven't seen under your foot and kill any sort of hope they have of being able to do their own creative take someday on a movie they want to see remade when technology advances beyond what we're capable of now and possibly breaking molds.   If you want to hate the movie, hate it, but don't teach your kids to hate a movie just because you've lost a sense of appreciation and respect for new grounds being tilled.  That is all. Reply as you will, I look forward to the sour grapes, because the kids in my life will make it into a fine wine because i'm not here to tell them their "remake" movies suck.

text: (Disclaimer: this is just my opinion, I can't speak for everyone) This should have never been remade... The original is amazing and no remake will ever be able to compare... Especially if you take out the music, comedic, and lighthearted aspects of the original. Elliot is supposed to be loving and goofy, and then there's Nora, the strong, independent, and motherly influence on Pete. And don't forget her father, whose crazy in all of the right ways to make him such an enjoyable character. And finally, Pete's adoptive family of swamp trash hicks that we all love to hate. All of these parts and characters made the movie so memorable to this day, and it seems as if none of it is going to even be attempted in this remake. Who knows, this might be a great movie, but it IS NOT Pete's Dragon. Don't try to remake perfection, it just won't end well.

text: I only saw the last 2/3 or so of the original "Pete's Dragon" in the theater. Why? Because we had started out watching "Star Wars," but I got scared during the cantina scene on Mos Eisley (I was 5). So an usher let my dad take me out of one theater and into the other one to make up for my fail. (We waited in line forever too...anyway...) It's odd that now Disney owns everything and happens to be re-releasing all of it at the same time. Getting a little too post-modern for my taste. So now Pete is a feral child? I guess the whole abusive Gogan (?) family thing won't work these days? Is it politically incorrect? But, you know, the original has such a great 1970s "Disney does olden times" feel a la  "Apple Dumpling Gang," plus with songs like "Brazzle Dazzle Day" and cheesy puppetry/mechanical effects when the dragon is "invisible" - that there's no way you can really replace or redo it without actually reinventing it. "Candle on the Water" is actually a pretty song too...

text: Executive producer OSBORNE, well I wouldn't be surprised is he was related to the green goblin with how the movie ended out. (I know it's probably not this fault alone but still...)  And welcome back to YOUR REMAKE IS FAILED !  This time we have a all time champion since it's the exact same studio who make the two version and let get it b*** r***** ! Thanks Disney glad to see you don't care about your classic anymore unless they are animated !   Before going to our main topic lets have a look back at the original movie ! Pete is a young boy who ran away of his adoptive family who were abusive. He is protected by a friendly looking doofus dragon : Elliott. He arrives in a fisher town with an impossible name. He start to fit in with some difficulties and when Lampie and his daughter Nora say he can stay a greedy pharmacian and his abusive family teams up to separate Pete and Elliott. After dealing with them Nora fianc√© Paul who where supposedly dead come back and Pete has a happy loving family. The movie was bright, colorfull and funny. Unless when things goes sour and then the ambiance is darker, there is a tempest and all. The movie mixed animation and Live action. A classic in Disney old movies.  Now lets have a look of the remakes trailer. So heres Pete is not a runnaway orphan, is a wild child. He is discovered by a family of three who adopts him and the perfect mom is understanding and loving bla bla bla... They discovered that he was protected by a giant "impressive" looking dragon. Somehow the army heards of that and it's the witch hunt all over again despite the best effort of Perfect Mama and the attachement of Pete.  A french youtube channel, Le fossoyeur de film (The movie's undertaker), has made a video about good and bad remakes. If you understand french, go see it. In those video Le fossoyeur de film says there is two categories of remakes. The ones who stick to the original and the one who tries to take liberties with it. Here at the first glance we would says they try to take liberties, since it has little but nothing to do with the original ones. I beg to differ, they do stick to the story, it's just the wrong ones ! Because for me it's not just a bad remake of Pete's Dragon, it's a bad remake of the Iron giant with some Free Willy elements. And Jungle Books too. So great job it's not just ONE bad remakes, it's THREE bad remakes ! Yeah my soul is dying !   So what is wrong so far. First of all Pete. Why is he a wild child all of sudden? Didn't Disney just release a Jungle Book remake? Seriously guys? Wasn't a abused orphan who try to escape a cruel system good enough for you? You actually thinks we like a child whith no identity to a poor orphan or is it how you saw those kids who run away? The the family, with a cute little girl so the ones in the publics and the feminist (or rather sexist) won't rant about it, does she really gonna brings anything to the story? The mom is so understanding that she is actually more iresponsible than a good mother. Pete's place is in an hospital, because someone who lived in the forest, let alone a child is likely to have health issue and I don't care about what kind of a great person you are but no one in their right mind will bring two children near a dragon and the army. So your place is in a mental ward madam. The husband is so transparent that even Paul who was there for less than 10 minutes in the original movie is more interesting. So we have a clich√© american family so nice and perfect comparing to the rest of the world we seen that I might barf. So it's pretty obvious it's lazy writing. No effort has been put into it. They didn't try to write likable charactere and find clich√© and excuses to avoid it.   Another thing I wants to point out is the ambiance. Why is it so dark? Seriously the ambiance in the original was as much a part of the story telling than the songs and the dialogues. You can't keep the same lowlight and restricted palets for the entire movie !   Is that supposed to be epic because to me it's dull and annoying and one of the biggest thing that said it's not worth watching it.  Oh and it's not worth going to the same studio as Peter Jackson for your special effects if it's for the dragon to look so fake. The only things you had for yourself was a occasion to have better special effect  than the original and you blew it. It looks fake, unfriendly and the movie wanted so much to be a blockbuster that they forgot the dragon was supposed to be able to take care of Pete, but that thing seems so big and wild I dont think he could help anyone because as I wrote before, Pete is a dragon version of Mary Poppins and the care bears, it's purpose is to help children. That thing can't help children.   So to sums it up, the movie is not remaking the right movie, the charactere writings is lazy, full of inconsistence and clich√© and where for his time the special effect of the original was memorable and impressive this one has no substance, is jsut for show and dissapointing. Disney, please next time hired Michael Bay, if you really have to make a lazy blockbuster remake, at least he will make something watchable and respect the concept better. For all the bad he has done or we thinks of him at least he has respected the franchise he adapted. Transformers was indeed about space robot on earth disguised as cars and Ninja Turtles about mutated ninja turtles fighting crime. That is Not Pete's Dragon. And if killing a movie was possible, that remake should be charged as murder.

text: To all naysayers & armchair critics... When I first saw the teaser several months ago, I had a feeling and I was not wrong. Best movie of the summer...best of 2016! And nobody knows it...! This movie has heart, soul, hope all rolled into a great story. It's not a remake but more a re-imagining of a tale that is what Disney does best but hasn't done in a long time. Critics were wrong about "Suicide Squad" but were so very right about "Pete's Dragon". I'm a man of 63 years. I grew up in Disneyland and the lore of Disney imagination. I have seen this film three times because it makes me feel GOOD, it makes me feel young.  If you told me a CGI dragon's love for a young boy would make me weep, I'd tell you that you were nuts. Elliot LIVES!!!!
